ne:472"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963585734367371, "span": {"begin": 1515, "end": 1518}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:545"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9957773089408875, "span": {"begin": 1519, "end": 1522}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DNA strand", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5392417311668396, "span": {"begin": 1589, "end": 1599}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:472"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9989295601844788, "span": {"begin": 1651, "end": 1654}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:545"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952856302261353, "span": {"begin": 1655, "end": 1658}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5595"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "extracellular signal-regulated kinase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9985801577568054, "span": {"begin": 1766, "end": 1803}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ERK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969804883003235, "span": {"begin": 1805, "end": 1808}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5599"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "c-Jun N-terminal kinase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984872937202454, "span": {"begin": 1811, "end": 1834}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25555"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.7587171792984009, "span": {"begin": 1817, "end": 1818}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "JNK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9980087280273438, "span": {"begin": 1836, "end": 1839}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p38", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9898756146430969, "span": {"begin": 1845, "end": 1848}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:472"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9958655834197998, "span": {"begin": 1912, "end": 1915}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:545"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9971556663513184, "span": {"begin": 1916, "end": 1919}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:472"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9972955584526062, "span": {"begin": 1982, "end": 1985}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:545"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9911651611328125, "span": {"begin": 1986, "end": 1989}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9967132806777954, "span": {"begin": 2008, "end": 2011}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012694"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "serine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.989727795124054, "span": {"begin": 2015, "end": 2021}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9947754144668579, "span": {"begin": 2053, "end": 2056}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9936071634292603, "span": {"begin": 2087, "end": 2090}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9974802136421204, "span": {"begin": 2146, "end": 2149}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9973438382148743, "span": {"begin": 2386, "end": 2389}}], "text": "There is strong evidence supporting the link between DNA strand breaks leading to altered stress response signaling. Single strand breaks (SSBs) or double strand breaks (DSBs) in DNA from both endogenous and exogenous sources can induce the DNA damage response, which can result in the induction of various signaling pathways (Baselet et al., 2019). DNA strand breaks are well known to lead to the activation of ATM and ATR as part of the normal DNA damage response (Abner and McKinnon, 2004; Baselet et al., 2019; Lee and McKinnon, 2007; Nagane et al., 2021; Sylvester et al., 2018; Thadathil et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020; Wang et al., 2017; Wang et al., 2016). While ATM tends to be recruited to DSBs, ATR is recruited by many types of DNA damage including both DSBs and SSBs (Mar&eacute;chal and Zou, 2013; Wang et al., 2017). Following a DNA DSB, the Mre11-Rad50-Nbs1 (MRN) complex senses and directly binds to the DNA ends at the site of the break, which subsequently activates ATM (Lee and McKinnon, 2007; Mar&eacute;chal and Zou, 2013). Following a DNA SSB, resection of the damaged strand by apurinic/apyrimidinic endonuclease (APE)1/APE2 is followed by coating the single-stranded DNA with replication protein A (RPA), where the recruitment of the ATR- ATR interacting protein (ATRIP) complex and the activation of ATR occurs (Caldecott, 2022; Mar&eacute;chal and Zou, 2013).&nbsp;  ATM and ATR can phosphorylate over 700 proteins (Nagane et al., 2021), and phosphorylation of key signaling proteins by ATM/ATR will alter signaling in their respective pathways. High levels of DNA strand breaks induced by exogenous stressors will enhance ATM/ATR activation and subsequently further activate downstream signaling, leading to downstream consequences. The extracellular signal-regulated kinase (ERK), c-Jun N-terminal kinase (JNK) and p38 MAPK subfamily pathways can be phosphorylated and activated by ATM/ATR (Ghahremani et al., 2002; Nagane et al., 2021). Additionally, ATM/ATR can phosphorylate p53 on serine 15 to enhance the stability of p53, leading to activation of the p53 pathway and changes in the transcriptional activity of p53 (Abner and McKinnon, 2004; Baselet et al., 2019; Lee and McKinnon, 2007; Nagane et al., 2021; Sylvester et al., 2018; Thadathil et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020; Wang et al., 2017; Wang et al., 2016). The apoptosis pathway downstream of p53 can also be activated by DNA strand breaks (Abner and McKinnon, 2004; Baselet et al., 2019; Lee and McKinnon, 2007; Thadathil et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020).&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:52:03 +0000 2026"}